04855nam a22007095i 9780812209839DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979744561  a97808122098397 a10.9783/97808122098392doi  a(DE-B1597)449847  a(OCoLC)881781672  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aLIT0040202bisacsh1 aSilyn Roberts, Siân, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGothic Subjects :bThe Transformation of Individualism in American Fiction, 1790-1861 /cSiân Silyn Roberts. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Gothic Enlightenment -- tChapter 1. Th e American Transformation of the British Individual -- tChapter 2. Captivity, Incorporation, and the Politics of Going Native -- tChapter 3. A Mind for the Gothic: Common Sense and the Problem of Local Culture -- tChapter 4. Population and the Limits of Civil Society in Nathaniel Hawthorne’s -- tChapter 5. Slavery and Gothic Form: Writing Race as the Bio- Novel -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeginning in the 1790s, North American readers developed an appetite for the gothic novel, as imported, reprinted, and pirated editions of British and European romances flooded the market alongside homegrown works. In Gothic Subjects, Siân Silyn Roberts accounts for the sudden and considerable appeal of the gothic during this period by contending that it prepared a culturally diverse American readership to think of itself as part of a transatlantic world through which goods, people, and information could circulate. By putting gothic literature in dialogue with the writings of Locke, Hume, Reid, Smith, Rousseau, and other major figures of the European Enlightenment, Silyn Roberts shows how the early American novel participated in the process of revising and transforming the figure of the modern individual for a fluid, contingent Atlantic population.Exploring works of fiction by Charles Brockden Brown, Leonora Sansay, Sally Sayward Barrell Keating Wood, Edgar Allan Poe, Robert Montgomery Bird, Nathaniel Hawthorne, and William Wells Brown, among others, Silyn Roberts argues that the gothic helped post-Revolutionary readers to think of themselves as political subjects. By reading the emergence of a national literary style in terms of its appropriation and reinterpretation of British cultural forms, Gothic Subjects situates itself at the crux of several important issues in American literary history: transatlantic literary relations, the connection between literature and political philosophy, the paradoxes of sovereign power, and the form of the novel. In doing so, Gothic Subjects powerfully rethinks some of our previous assumptions about the cultural work of the American gothic tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnlightenmentxInfluence. 0aIndividualism in literature. 0aNational characteristics, American, in literature. 4aCultural Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220983940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812209839423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812209839.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EB